value.value: Particulate environmental material which is composed primarily of carbon particles formed through the incomplete combustion of hydrocarbons.
Water ice which contains material liberated during an erosion process.
Uncompacted snow containing trapped atmospheric gases.

definition.value: Described as having a fluffy appearance.
A process during which the mass of ice constituting a glacier increases.

value.value: A process during which a part of a glacier breaks away from the main mass.

definition.value: Calving is usually caused by the expansion of glaciers.

value.value: A process during which a part of a glacier breaks away from the main mass as an iceberg.

definition.value: Calving is usually caused by the expansion of glaciers.

label.value: calving of ice from an iceberg

value.value: A process during which a part of an iceberg breaks away from the main mass.
Sediment which has been transported through the marine water column, settling on the seafloor.

definition.value: Particles of marine sediment are primarily generated by 1) processes in terrestrial systems and transported to the marine realm by the action of rivers or aeolian processes (amongst other routes) , 2) marine organisms, 3) chemical processes in seawater, or 4) cosmogeneous input.

value.value: Marine sediment soured from either terrestrial systems, marine organisms, seawater and or cosmogeneous sources, which is transported through the marine water column, and accumulates within shallow regions of the oceanic basin close to continents, such as the continental shelf, or continental slope.
A water body which is located in a depression within the surface of a glacier.

definition.value: A material accumulation process during which solid particles are pulled through a water body by gravitation or centrifugal force and which ends when they settle on a solid surface.

value.value: An ablation zone which is part of a glacier.

This class is more fully defined as: "The part of the glacier, usually at lower elevations, where ablation exceeds accumulation in magnitude, that is, where the cumulative mass balance relative to the start of the mass-balance year is negative. Unless qualified, for example by giving a date within the year, references to the ablation zone refer to its extent at the end of the mass-balance year. The extent of the ablation zone can vary strongly from year to year. A synonym of ablation area." - GCW Terminology and Vocabulary Assessment Report 2018”, GCW report #23/2018

Particulate environmental material which is composed primarily of dust, rock, and soot, as well as the microbial communities associated with these materials, deposited on an ice mass by an aeolian process.
A vertical thaw hole within an ice mass, formed as a result of ice melt associated with local temperature increases, due to increased absorption of solar radiation by cryoconite deposits.

definition.value: This class doesn't refer to the site but instead the depression or hole and therefore the adjacency to the cryoconite itself.

value.value: A water body which forms as a result of localised melting taking place on the surface of a glacier or a mass of sea ice and which is contained in the cavity formed by such melting.
A channel through which brine flows.
A material accumulation process during which brine droplets, trapped between ice crystals formed during seawater freezing, form brine channels.

definition.value: This process may be considered a material accumulation process as it is the accumulation of brine droplets which form the channels.
A process during which a portion of some environmental material is converted into a different material or a collection of materials.

Experimental class for structural purposes not recommended for annotation. A material transformation process only refers to ENVO:environmental material classes (e.g. bulk and typically impure substances), rather than transformations converting a specific chemical into another.

value.value: A material transformation process during which seawater freezes into sea ice.
A material transformation process during which brine is formed due to the expulsion of salt during frazil formation or a seawater freezing process.

definition.value: Expelled salt accumulates in brine droplets, which remain in a liquid state due to their increased salinity.

value.value: New ice which is composed frazil which has congealed into a thin sheet.

definition.value: Typically 3 to 4 millimeters in diameter. These new ice classes refer to both marine water and fresh water ice. If using this term for annotation, use it in conjunction with another envo term to express whether the ice is in a marine, freshwater, or other system.

value.value: A new ice formation process during which small, needle-like crystals consisting of nearly pure fresh water, form due to the freezing of open, turbulent, supercooled water.
A channel which traverses an ice mass floating on a water body and bridges the atmosphere to the underlying water through its internal cavity.
A melt pond which has a surface exposed to the atmosphere.
A melt pond which is completely encased in ice and thus not directly exposed to the atmosphere or underlying water.

definition.value: In practice, there may be some openings which are small relative to the surface footprint of the meltpond.

value.value: A lake which is comprised of meltwater located underneath or within a glacier.
A process during which material entities are added to a landform or to a feature upon the landform.

label.value: desublimation of water vapour into ice

definition.value: A desublimation process during which water vapour is frozen into water ice.

value.value: An ice formation process during which water is frozen into a form of new ice such as frazil, grease ice, slush, or shuga.
A sea ice formation process during which new ice crystals freeze together, forming nilas, a thin, elastic, continuous, ice sheet of a transparent gray color.
A sea ice formation process during which water freezes to the bottom of an existing nilas ice floe creating a thicker ice floe known as young ice.
A sea ice formation process during which seawater freezes onto young ice during the cold season, forming first year ice.

definition.value: First year ice that survives melting during spring and summer can transition to second year ice.

value.value: A sea ice formation process during which seawater freezes onto first year ice during the cold season, forming second year sea ice.

definition.value: Second year ice forms from first year ice which has previously survived one melt season.

value.value: A sea ice formation process during which seawater freezes into second year ice during the cold season, forming multiyear ice.

definition.value: Multiyear ice forms from second year ice which has previously survived at least two melt seasons.

value.value: Water ice which is formed from freezing water and is suspended in a water body.

definition.value: sea ice types include frazil, grease ice, slush, and shuga. These new ice classes refer to both marine water and fresh water ice. If using this term for annotation, use it in conjunction with another envo term to express whether the ice is in a marine, freshwater, or other system.

value.value: An ice mass which forms a cohesive and contiguous sheet of water ice, floating upon the surface of a water body.

Ice floes can exist in sea ice, in rivers or lakes. The WMO offers the following extent-based classification. Floe giant: Over 10 km across.
Floe vast: 2-10 km across. Floe big: 500-2000 m across. Floe medium: 100-500 m across. Floe small: 20-100 m across. Ice cake: Less than 20 m across. Small ice cake: Less than 2 m across.
An ice floe which is formed from frozen sea water, and floats upon the surface of a marine water body.
A sea ice floe which has a rounded or circular shape and raised rims.
A sea ice floe which is thin, elastic, continuous, and of a transparent gray color, which results from the freezing of new ice.
A sea ice floe which is inflexible and thicker than nilas.
Sea ice which has formed over a single freezing season.

Sea ice develops from young ice; thickness from 0.3 to 2 meters (1 to 6.6 feet).  Sea ice be subdivided into thin first-year ice (white ice), medium first-year ice, and thick first-year ice.  First-year ice is distinguished from older ice primarily by having a higher salinity. Undeformed first-year ice differs from older ice in that it is smoother and lacks refrozen melt ponds. Characteristically level where undisturbed by pressure, but where ridges occur, they  distinguished by being larger, more angular, and more porous than multiyear ridges.
Sea ice which is thicker than first year ice, and has survived a seasonal melting process.
Sea ice which is thicker than second year ice, and has survived more than two seasonal melting process.
A layer which consists of a thin aggregate of frazil ice crystals, which float upon the surface of a water body.

definition.value: Within a marine system, grease ice makes the ocean surface resemble an oil slick.

value.value: New ice, which is spongy, lumpy and opaque, and forms from water which freezes in an agitated water body.

definition.value: These new ice classes refer to both marine water and fresh water ice. If using this term for annotation, use it in conjunction with another envo term to express whether the ice is in a marine, freshwater, or other system.

value.value: A slurry of frazil, snow, and liquid water.

definition.value: These new ice classes refer to both marine water and fresh water ice. If using this term for annotation, use it in conjunction with another envo term to express whether the ice is in a marine, freshwater, or other system.

value.value: A layer which consists of slush ice.

definition.value: A new ice formation process in which slush ice is formed.
A new ice formation process in which shuga is formed.

value.value: A freshwater lake which fills a depression formed by the erosion of thermokarst caused by permafrost thaw.

definition.value: Continued thawing of the permafrost substrate can lead to the drainage and eventual disappearance of thermokarst lakes, leaving only the landform, thermokarst depression behind.
